<font color="#FF0000">PROTEST</font><br>
<tt>Wed Nov 27 23:01:49 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I protested against the war from 1964 through to the end. <br>
It was the center of my life, the focus of my every day.<br>
I was in S.D.S., an extreamist in the eyes of some. Then<br>
I didn't think I was too extreame, now I am not sure. I was<br>
clear that my &quot;enemy&quot; was not the soldiers, the grunts or<br>
&quot;cannon fodder. My enemy was those who felt that the war<br>
was justifiable for economic and 'policital' reasons. I <br>
was against the war on political and economic grounds. Now<br>
that I have three children, all of who are approaching the <br>
age where they may be faced with such choices I know that<br>
the main reason the war was wrong is because we did not<br>
value human life. Then I raged at the war, now I have learned<br>
to cry about the horror of it. <br><br>
I think that the time I and others spent fighting (protesting) against<br>
the war helped in some way to shorten the war. To me this<br>
means that I helped to save lives, and the time, effort<br>
and disruption to me was well worth it. I am proud of what I<br>
did and understanding of those who fought. It was not clear<br>
then what was right and what was wrong. I have come to believe<br>
that people find their own paths in life and I cannot <br>
accuse those who chose to fight. <br><br>
To those who still suffer the pain of that time and their experience,<br>
we all did the best we could, hoping it was the right thing<br>
to do. Peace to yu brothers and sisters.
